{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"126babe6-f032-49c6-9eef-39ca7ab71f8a","content":"Here's a step-by-step approach:\n\n**1. Get into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**Alternatives if `dotnet-trace` can't be installed in the container:**\n\n- **`dotnet-monitor`** – deploy as a sidecar container; exposes an HTTP API to collect traces without modifying your app container.\n- **`kubectl cp`** – copy the `.nettrace` file out of the pod:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n  ```\n\n> **Tip:** For Windows containers, `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` is useful for a quick live view of CPU %, GC, and thread pool stats *before* committing to a full trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"87ad3b44-7c39-4faf-a1c9-e61a9f8687b1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":402,"requestId":"501D:1FBC5F:1F4CFB:26FAB0:69F5510F"},"id":"cedc7763-1379-4995-87dd-3539bea960df","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:19:20.913Z","parentId":"f69e8ffc-78d2-4b3b-ac7c-589b9d30fc2c"}
